  "text": "In 1993 interest in the postulated involvement of the opiate system in development, prenatally through old age, remained high and even increased, but there was little attention to the possible opiate modulation of sexual behavior, dwindling from previous years. There was a finding, however, that endogenous peptides may control testosterone biosynthesis through an interaction with the vasopressin system, because naloxone increased testosterone production by Leydig cells and reduced testicular vasopressin, but only in the injected testis [CITATION_1] .",
